<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1046,1611]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,299,1190,1215]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Ecology.</emphasis>
Most specimens were collected together with 
<taxonomicName box="[855,1117,1190,1214]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Leptalpheus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corderoae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[855,1117,1190,1214]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Leptalpheus corderoae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1129,1223,1190,1215]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1129,1223,1190,1215]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, from burrows of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,450,1227,1251]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Lepidophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bocourti">
<emphasis box="[151,450,1227,1251]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Lepidophthalmus bocourti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as well as from an unidentified host burrowing near mangroves close to burrows of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,361,1262,1286]" class="Malacostraca" family="Upogebiidae" genus="Upogebia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dawsoni">
<emphasis box="[151,361,1262,1286]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Upogebia dawsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="581" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1046,1611]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1298,1323]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Remarks.</emphasis>
Specimens collected in Estero Pérula fit well to the description and illustrations of 
<taxonomicName box="[1285,1436,1299,1323]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Leptalpheus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hendrickxi">
<emphasis box="[1285,1436,1299,1323]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">L. hendrickxi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Anker" box="[295,446,1334,1359]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" refString="Anker, A. (2011) Six new species and three new records of infaunal alpheid shrimps from the genera Leptalpheus Williams, 1965 and Fenneralpheus Felder &amp; Manning, 1986 (Crustacea, Decapoda). Zootaxa, 3041, 1 - 38." type="journal article" year="2011">
Anker (
<number box="[381,439,1335,1359]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and a few small differences observed in our specimens may be related to size. In large specimens from Estero Pérula, the stylocerite may slightly exceeds the anterior margin of the first antennular article (
<figureCitation box="[159,236,1406,1431]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[205,1383,199,1274]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[204,1386,195,1276]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leptalpheus hendrickxi Anker, 2011 (A, C, D, E, EMU- 10054; B, LEMA-CR 57). A, B, anterior part of carapace and appendages, dorsal view; C, major cheliped, lateral view; D, minor cheliped, lateral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/231610/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">
Figs. 
<number box="[222,236,1407,1431]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B), whilst in specimens of 
<collectingCountry box="[568,657,1407,1430]" name="Panama" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Panama</collectingCountry>
it does not. The propodus of the fifth pereiopod (
<figureCitation box="[1208,1273,1406,1431]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[205,1383,199,1274]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[204,1386,195,1276]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leptalpheus hendrickxi Anker, 2011 (A, C, D, E, EMU- 10054; B, LEMA-CR 57). A, B, anterior part of carapace and appendages, dorsal view; C, major cheliped, lateral view; D, minor cheliped, lateral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/231610/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">
Fig. 
<number box="[1259,1273,1407,1431]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
E) bears seven rows of ventrodistal setae (instead of five illustrated in the 
<collectingCountry box="[818,907,1443,1466]" name="Panama" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Panama</collectingCountry>
material), but this might be a normal variation for this species which is not well known. In large specimens, the armature of the merus and propodus of the major cheliped is more pronounced, with an additional row of granules extending from the mesial surface of the propodus to the ventral surface of the pollex (
<figureCitation box="[579,650,1550,1575]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[205,1383,199,1274]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[204,1386,195,1276]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leptalpheus hendrickxi Anker, 2011 (A, C, D, E, EMU- 10054; B, LEMA-CR 57). A, B, anterior part of carapace and appendages, dorsal view; C, major cheliped, lateral view; D, minor cheliped, lateral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/231610/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">
Fig. 
<number box="[635,650,1551,1575]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
C). The collection of 
<taxonomicName box="[905,1057,1550,1574]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Leptalpheus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hendrickxi">
<emphasis box="[905,1057,1550,1574]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">L. hendrickxi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Jalisco, 
<collectingCountry box="[1195,1284,1550,1575]" name="Mexico" pageId="8" pageNumber="581">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, represents a significant extension of the species’ distribution range by ca. 
<quantity box="[838,937,1586,1611]" metricMagnitude="6" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" unit="km" value="3000.0">3000 km</quantity>
(= 
<number box="[976,1004,1587,1611]" pageId="8" pageNumber="581" value="11.0">11</number>
° of latitude) to the north.
</paragraph>
